1
00:00:55,589 --> 00:00:57,024
Dr. Oppenheimer.

2
00:00:58,559 --> 00:00:59,860
Dr. Oppenheimer.

3
00:01:01,095 --> 00:01:04,965
As we begin, I believe you have a statement to read into the record.

4
00:01:06,467 --> 00:01:07,834
Yes, Your Honor.

5
00:01:07,835 --> 00:01:10,269
We're not judges, Doctor.

6
00:01:10,270 --> 00:01:12,071
No.

7
00:01:12,072 --> 00:01:13,507
Of course.

8
00:01:18,712 --> 00:01:21,347
Members of the security board.

9
00:01:21,348 --> 00:01:25,485
The so-called and derogatory information in your indictment of me

10
00:01:25,486 --> 00:01:27,019
cannot be fairly understood,

11
00:01:27,020 --> 00:01:31,023
except in the context of my life and my work.

12
00:01:31,024 --> 00:01:33,494
How long did he testify?

13
00:01:34,094 --> 00:01:35,929
Honestly, I forget.

14
00:01:37,264 --> 00:01:39,232
The whole hearing took a month.

15
00:01:39,233 --> 00:01:40,800
An ordeal.

16
00:01:40,801 --> 00:01:43,737
I've only read the transcripts, but...

17
00:01:45,139 --> 00:01:47,073
Who'd want to justify their whole life?

18
00:01:47,074 --> 00:01:49,742
- You weren't there? - As chairman, I wasn't allowed to be.

19
00:01:49,743 --> 00:01:52,445
Are they really going to ask about it?

20
00:01:52,446 --> 00:01:54,280
It was years ago.

21
00:01:54,281 --> 00:01:55,983
- Four years ago. - Five.

22
00:01:56,817 --> 00:01:58,351
Oppenheimer still divides America.

23
00:01:58,352 --> 00:02:01,387
The committee is gonna want to know where you stood.

24
00:02:01,388 --> 00:02:05,158
Senator Thurmond asked me to say not to feel that you're on trial.

25
00:02:05,159 --> 00:02:08,427
Aw. Funny, I didn't till you just said that.

26
00:02:08,428 --> 00:02:09,562
Really, Mr. Strauss...

27
00:02:09,563 --> 00:02:11,097
It's Admiral.

28
00:02:11,098 --> 00:02:13,332
Admiral Strauss. This is a formality.

29
00:02:13,333 --> 00:02:15,768
President Eisenhower has asked you to be in his cabinet.

30
00:02:15,769 --> 00:02:17,637
Senate really has no choice but to confirm you.

31
00:02:17,638 --> 00:02:19,972
And if they bring up Oppenheimer?

32
00:02:19,973 --> 00:02:22,508
When they bring up Oppenheimer, you answer honestly.

33
00:02:22,509 --> 00:02:24,744
No senator can deny you did your duty.

34
00:02:24,745 --> 00:02:27,046
It'll be uncomfortable.

35
00:02:27,047 --> 00:02:29,283
Who'd want to justify their whole life?

36
00:02:34,188 --> 00:02:37,157
Why did you leave the United States?

37
00:02:38,725 --> 00:02:42,395
I, uh... I wanted to study the new physics.

38
00:02:42,396 --> 00:02:44,330
Was there nowhere here?

39
00:02:44,331 --> 00:02:47,868
I thought Berkeley had the leading theoretical physics department.

40
00:02:48,502 --> 00:02:50,436
Yes. Once I had built it.

41
00:02:50,437 --> 00:02:51,938
But first I had to go to Europe.

42
00:02:51,939 --> 00:02:55,474
I went to Cambridge to study under Patrick Blackett.

43
00:02:55,475 --> 00:02:58,011
Were you happier there than in America?

44
00:02:58,545 --> 00:03:00,213
- Happier? - Yes.

45
00:03:04,151 --> 00:03:05,918
No.

46
00:03:05,919 --> 00:03:07,120
No, I, uh...

47
00:03:10,157 --> 00:03:11,925
I was homesick, um,

48
00:03:12,793 --> 00:03:14,828
emotionally immature,

49
00:03:15,629 --> 00:03:20,634
troubled by visions of a hidden universe.

50
00:03:32,746 --> 00:03:33,814
Useless in the lab.

51
00:03:39,152 --> 00:03:40,821
Christ, Oppenheimer.

52
00:03:41,588 --> 00:03:43,256
Have you had any sleep?

53
00:03:45,092 --> 00:03:46,359
Start again.

54
00:03:46,360 --> 00:03:48,795
I need to go to the lecture, sir.

55
00:03:49,263 --> 00:03:50,263
Why?

56
00:03:50,831 --> 00:03:52,199
It's Niels Bohr.

57
00:03:54,968 --> 00:03:56,303
I'd completely forgot.

58
00:03:57,104 --> 00:03:59,539
All right. Let's go.

59
00:04:01,341 --> 00:04:04,411
Oh, no, not you, Oppenheimer. You finish coating those plates.

60
00:04:44,885 --> 00:04:48,788
Quantum physics is not a step forward.

61
00:04:48,789 --> 00:04:52,692
It is a new way to understand reality.

62
00:04:52,693 --> 00:04:54,393
Einstein's opened the door.

63
00:04:54,394 --> 00:04:58,664
Now we are peering through, seeing a world inside our world.

64
00:04:58,665 --> 00:05:03,703
A world of energy and paradox that not everyone can accept.

65
00:05:46,880 --> 00:05:49,249
Yeah... Are you all right?

66
00:05:50,017 --> 00:05:52,885
Niels, meet J. Robert Oppenheimer.

67
00:05:52,886 --> 00:05:54,553
What's the J stand for?

68
00:05:54,554 --> 00:05:56,188
Nothing, apparently.

69
00:05:56,189 --> 00:05:58,357
You were at my lecture. You asked the only good question.

70
00:05:58,358 --> 00:06:00,292
No one's denying his insight.

71
00:06:00,293 --> 00:06:02,763
It's his laboratory work that leaves a little to be desired.

72
00:06:03,630 --> 00:06:04,997
I heard you give the same lectu...

73
00:06:04,998 --> 00:06:07,533
At Harvard, yes, and you asked the same question.

74
00:06:07,534 --> 00:06:08,667
Why ask again?

75
00:06:08,668 --> 00:06:10,137
Hadn't liked your answer.

76
00:06:11,371 --> 00:06:13,906
- Did you like it better yesterday? - A lot.

77
00:06:13,907 --> 00:06:18,911
You can lift the stone without being ready for the snake that's revealed.

78
00:06:18,912 --> 00:06:21,080
Now it seems you're ready.

79
00:06:21,081 --> 00:06:23,482
But you don't enjoy the lab?

80
00:06:23,483 --> 00:06:26,352
So get out of Cambridge with its beakers and potions.

81
00:06:26,353 --> 00:06:29,322
Go somewhere they'll let you think.

82
00:06:30,290 --> 00:06:31,391
Where?

83
00:06:32,726 --> 00:06:33,759
Göttingen.

84
00:06:33,760 --> 00:06:35,728
- Born. - Born.

85
00:06:35,729 --> 00:06:37,563
Get to Germany. Study under Max Born.

86
00:06:37,564 --> 00:06:40,266
Learn the ways of theory.

87
00:06:40,267 --> 00:06:41,368
I'll send word.

88
00:06:42,502 --> 00:06:44,271
Wormhole.

89
00:06:45,806 --> 00:06:47,273
How's your mathematics?

90
00:06:47,274 --> 00:06:49,108
Not good enough for the physicist he wants to be.

91
00:06:49,109 --> 00:06:51,243
Algebra's like sheet music.

92
00:06:51,244 --> 00:06:53,646
The important thing isn't "can you read music?"

93
00:06:53,647 --> 00:06:55,114
It's "can you hear it?"

94
00:06:55,115 --> 00:06:57,851
Can you hear the music, Robert?

95
00:06:58,819 --> 00:07:00,720
Yes, I can.

96
00:08:36,149 --> 00:08:38,018
The senator from Wyoming.

97
00:08:38,818 --> 00:08:40,119
Admiral Strauss,

98
00:08:40,120 --> 00:08:41,787
I'm interested in your relationship with

99
00:08:41,788 --> 00:08:43,522
Dr. J. Robert Oppenheimer.

100
00:08:43,523 --> 00:08:45,358
You met him in 1947?

101
00:08:45,759 --> 00:08:47,326
Correct.

102
00:08:47,327 --> 00:08:49,828
You were commissioner of the Atomic Energy Commission?

103
00:08:49,829 --> 00:08:54,868
I was, but I actually met Robert in my capacity as board member

104
00:08:55,235 --> 00:08:57,570
of the Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton,

105
00:08:57,571 --> 00:09:00,806
because after the war he was world renowned

106
00:09:00,807 --> 00:09:02,274
as the great man of physics,

107
00:09:02,275 --> 00:09:06,446
and I was determined to get him to run the Institute.

108
00:09:16,056 --> 00:09:18,824
Dr. Oppenheimer. An honor.

109
00:09:18,825 --> 00:09:19,959
Mr. Strauss.

110
00:09:19,960 --> 00:09:22,194
It's pronounced "straws."

111
00:09:22,195 --> 00:09:23,629
Oh-ppenheimer, Oppenheimer.

112
00:09:23,630 --> 00:09:25,699
Whatever way you say it, they know I'm Jewish.

113
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:29,902
I'm president of Temple Emanu-El in Manhattan.

114
00:09:29,903 --> 00:09:32,438
"Straws" is just the Southern pronunciation.

115
00:09:32,439 --> 00:09:34,773
Anyway, welcome to the Institute.

116
00:09:34,774 --> 00:09:36,308
I think you could be very happy here.

117
00:09:36,309 --> 00:09:38,410
Yes, well, you'll love the commute.

118
00:09:38,411 --> 00:09:41,113
The position comes with that house for you and your wife,

119
00:09:41,114 --> 00:09:43,282
and your... Is it two children?

120
00:09:43,283 --> 00:09:44,316
Yes, two.

121
00:09:44,317 --> 00:09:47,119
I'm a great admirer of your work.

122
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:49,421
And you're a physicist by training, Mr. Strauss?

123
00:09:49,422 --> 00:09:51,557
I'm sorry, common room, four o'clock tea.

124
00:09:51,558 --> 00:09:54,593
No, I'm not trained in physics or anything else.

125
00:09:54,594 --> 00:09:55,761
I'm a self-made man.

126
00:09:55,762 --> 00:09:58,163
Ah. I can relate to that. Really?

127
00:09:58,164 --> 00:10:00,266
Yes, my father was one.

128
00:10:01,301 --> 00:10:04,170
And this would be your office.

129
00:10:13,346 --> 00:10:15,948
I'm told he's there most afternoons.

130
00:10:15,949 --> 00:10:17,516
You know, I've always wondered

131
00:10:17,517 --> 00:10:21,087
why you didn't involve him in the Manhattan Project.

132
00:10:22,922 --> 00:10:25,090
Greatest scientific mind of our time.

133
00:10:25,091 --> 00:10:27,026
Of his time.

134
00:10:27,027 --> 00:10:29,228
Einstein published his Theory of Relativity

135
00:10:29,229 --> 00:10:32,731
more than 40 years ago now.

136
00:10:32,732 --> 00:10:35,734
But never embraced the quantum world it revealed.

137
00:10:35,735 --> 00:10:37,337
"God doesn't play dice."

138
00:10:37,904 --> 00:10:39,471
Precisely.

139
00:10:39,472 --> 00:10:42,074
You never thought of studying physics formally, Mr. Strauss?

140
00:10:42,075 --> 00:10:44,643
I had offers, but I chose to sell shoes.

141
00:10:44,644 --> 00:10:47,981
Lewis Strauss was once a lowly shoe salesman.

142
00:10:48,882 --> 00:10:50,884
No, just a shoe salesman.

143
00:10:54,354 --> 00:10:56,388
I'd love to introduce you.

144
00:10:56,389 --> 00:10:57,524
No need.

145
00:10:58,091 --> 00:10:59,993
I have known him for years.

146
00:11:21,648 --> 00:11:22,648
Albert.

147
00:11:27,153 --> 00:11:29,054
What was that?

148
00:11:29,055 --> 00:11:31,357
What did you say to him?

149
00:11:33,326 --> 00:11:34,761
Oh, he's fine.

150
00:11:36,529 --> 00:11:41,066
Mr. Strauss, there are things in my past you ought to be aware of.

151
00:11:41,067 --> 00:11:44,770
Well, as chairman of the AEC, I have access to your security file.

152
00:11:44,771 --> 00:11:45,838
I've read it.

153
00:11:45,839 --> 00:11:47,740
You're not worried? No.

154
00:11:47,741 --> 00:11:50,209
Why would I be worried after everything you've done for your country?

155
00:11:50,210 --> 00:11:51,643
Well, times change, Mr. Strauss.

156
00:11:51,644 --> 00:11:53,679
Well, the purpose of this institute

157
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:56,382
is to provide a haven for independent minds.

158
00:11:57,117 --> 00:11:58,350
That's you.

159
00:11:58,351 --> 00:12:00,919
You are the man for the job.

160
00:12:00,920 --> 00:12:02,721
Well, then I'll consider it.

161
00:12:02,722 --> 00:12:05,258
I'll see you at the AEC meeting tomorrow.

162
00:12:09,929 --> 00:12:12,364
This is one of the most prestigious appointments in the country.

163
00:12:12,365 --> 00:12:15,167
Yes, with a great commute.

164
00:12:15,168 --> 00:12:16,803
That's why I'm considering it.

165
00:12:17,971 --> 00:12:20,305
So, Dr. Oppenheimer brought your attention to

166
00:12:20,306 --> 00:12:22,007
his past associations

167
00:12:22,008 --> 00:12:23,475
before you appointed him?

168
00:12:23,476 --> 00:12:26,245
- Yes. - And they didn't concern you?

169
00:12:26,246 --> 00:12:28,046
Just then I was entirely consumed

170
00:12:28,047 --> 00:12:29,782
with what he must have said to Einstein

171
00:12:29,783 --> 00:12:32,785
to sour him on me.

172
00:12:35,155 --> 00:12:36,355
But later?

173
00:12:36,356 --> 00:12:38,624
Well, we all know what happened later.

174
00:12:38,625 --> 00:12:40,659
Doctor, your time in Europe,

175
00:12:40,660 --> 00:12:42,394
you seemed to meet with a wide range

176
00:12:42,395 --> 00:12:43,962
of other countries' physicists.

177
00:12:43,963 --> 00:12:45,030
Yes, that's right.

178
00:12:45,031 --> 00:12:47,100
Any Russians?

179
00:12:48,201 --> 00:12:49,768
None that spring to mind.

180
00:12:49,769 --> 00:12:51,804
If you'll just allow me to continue with my statement...

181
00:12:51,805 --> 00:12:55,775
Mr. Robb, you'll have ample opportunity to cross-examine.

182
00:12:58,011 --> 00:13:01,346
After Göttingen, I moved on to Leiden in Holland,

183
00:13:01,347 --> 00:13:03,916
where I first met Isidor Rabi.

184
00:13:03,917 --> 00:13:05,685
Excuse me.

185
00:13:10,323 --> 00:13:12,391
A Yank, lecturing on the new physics?

186
00:13:12,392 --> 00:13:13,859
This I have to hear.

187
00:13:13,860 --> 00:13:15,994
I'm an American myself.

188
00:13:15,995 --> 00:13:17,363
How surprising.

189
00:13:18,298 --> 00:13:20,833
Let me know if you need any help with the English.

190
00:13:34,848 --> 00:13:36,749
Wait, what's he saying?

191
00:13:47,660 --> 00:13:48,494
No, thank you.

192
00:13:48,495 --> 00:13:50,395
It's a long way to Zurich.

193
00:13:50,396 --> 00:13:53,333
You get any skinnier, we're gonna lose you between the seat cushions.

194
00:13:53,967 --> 00:13:55,033
I'm Rabi.

195
00:13:55,034 --> 00:13:56,335
Oppenheimer.

196
00:13:56,336 --> 00:13:58,370
I caught your lecture on molecules.

197
00:13:58,371 --> 00:14:00,172
Caught some of it.

198
00:14:00,173 --> 00:14:02,774
We're a couple of New York Jews. How do you know Dutch?

199
00:14:02,775 --> 00:14:05,544
Well, I thought I'd better learn it when I got here this semester.

200
00:14:05,545 --> 00:14:09,181
You learned enough Dutch in six weeks to give a lecture on quantum mechanics?

201
00:14:09,182 --> 00:14:10,616
Wanted to challenge myself.

202
00:14:10,617 --> 00:14:13,118
Quantum physics wasn't challenging enough.

203
00:14:13,119 --> 00:14:14,853
Schvitzer. Schvitzer?

204
00:14:14,854 --> 00:14:16,321
Show-off.

205
00:14:16,322 --> 00:14:18,557
Dutch in six weeks, but you never learned Yiddish?

206
00:14:18,558 --> 00:14:20,792
They don't speak it so much my side of the park.

207
00:14:20,793 --> 00:14:22,395
Screw you.

208
00:14:23,329 --> 00:14:26,565
- You homesick? - Oh, you know it.

209
00:14:26,566 --> 00:14:29,868
Ever get the feeling our kind isn't entirely welcome here?

210
00:14:29,869 --> 00:14:30,937
Physicists?

211
00:14:31,371 --> 00:14:32,371
That's funny.

212
00:14:32,372 --> 00:14:34,473
Not in the department.

213
00:14:34,474 --> 00:14:35,875
They're all Jewish too.

214
00:14:38,011 --> 00:14:39,245
Eat.

215
00:14:41,681 --> 00:14:43,916
There's a German you have to seek out.

216
00:14:44,817 --> 00:14:47,253
Heisenberg. Right.

217
00:14:56,296 --> 00:15:00,532
One might be led to the presumption that behind the quantum world,

218
00:15:00,533 --> 00:15:04,236
there still hides a real world in which causality holds,

219
00:15:04,237 --> 00:15:08,974
but such speculations seem to us, to say it explicitly, fruitless.

220
00:15:08,975 --> 00:15:10,943
Thank you. Have a great day.

221
00:15:15,248 --> 00:15:17,382
Werner. Wonderful. Thank you.

222
00:15:17,383 --> 00:15:19,051
Dr. Oppenheimer.

223
00:15:19,052 --> 00:15:23,088
Oppenheimer, yes. I liked your paper on molecules.

224
00:15:23,089 --> 00:15:24,489
Probably because you inspired it.

225
00:15:24,490 --> 00:15:26,191
If I inspire anything else, let me know.

226
00:15:26,192 --> 00:15:27,259
We could publish together.

227
00:15:27,260 --> 00:15:29,027
I have to get back to America.

228
00:15:29,028 --> 00:15:30,662
Why?

229
00:15:30,663 --> 00:15:33,031
There's no one there taking quantum mechanics seriously.

230
00:15:33,032 --> 00:15:34,566
That's exactly why.

231
00:15:34,567 --> 00:15:37,169
He's pining for the canyons of Manhattan.

232
00:15:37,170 --> 00:15:39,471
Canyons of New Mexico.

233
00:15:39,472 --> 00:15:40,639
You're from New Mexico?

234
00:15:40,640 --> 00:15:42,374
No. New York, but my brother and I

235
00:15:42,375 --> 00:15:44,876
have a ranch outside Santa Fe.

236
00:15:44,877 --> 00:15:46,712
That's the America I miss right now.

237
00:15:46,713 --> 00:15:49,082
Then it's best you get home, cowboys.

238
00:15:50,183 --> 00:15:51,450
That's him.

239
00:15:51,451 --> 00:15:54,787
No, me and horses? I don't think so.

240
00:15:55,288 --> 00:15:56,756
Nice to meet you.

241
00:15:58,491 --> 00:16:00,659
Did you ever encounter Heisenberg again?

242
00:16:00,660 --> 00:16:03,396
Not in person, no, but, uh...

243
00:16:04,831 --> 00:16:07,266
you might say our paths crossed.

244
00:16:08,401 --> 00:16:09,901
On returning to America,

245
00:16:09,902 --> 00:16:13,072
I accepted positions at both Caltech and up at Berkeley.

246
00:16:37,463 --> 00:16:39,465
Dr. Lawrence, I presume?

247
00:16:41,467 --> 00:16:43,735
- You must be Oppenheimer. - Yes.

248
00:16:43,736 --> 00:16:46,204
I hear you want to start a school of quantum theory.

249
00:16:46,205 --> 00:16:48,073
I am starting it. Next door.

250
00:16:48,074 --> 00:16:49,274
They put you in there?

251
00:16:49,275 --> 00:16:50,575
I asked for it.

252
00:16:50,576 --> 00:16:52,544
Wanted to be close to you experimentalists.

253
00:16:52,545 --> 00:16:54,146
Theory will get you only so far, huh?

254
00:16:54,147 --> 00:16:56,348
We're building a machine to accelerate electrons.

255
00:16:56,349 --> 00:16:57,416
Magnificent.

256
00:16:57,417 --> 00:16:59,017
Would you like to help?

257
00:16:59,018 --> 00:17:00,819
Build it? Oh, no.

258
00:17:00,820 --> 00:17:02,187
No, no.

259
00:17:02,188 --> 00:17:04,623
But I am working on theories I'd like to test with it.

260
00:17:04,624 --> 00:17:05,857
When do you start teaching?

261
00:17:05,858 --> 00:17:07,426
I've got my first in an hour.

262
00:17:07,427 --> 00:17:09,662
- Seminar? - Pupil.

263
00:17:10,196 --> 00:17:12,798
One student? That's it?

264
00:17:12,799 --> 00:17:15,200
I'm teaching something no one here has dreamt of.

265
00:17:15,201 --> 00:17:17,536
But once people start hearing what you can do with it...

266
00:17:17,537 --> 00:17:19,172
There's no going back.

267
00:17:21,507 --> 00:17:24,176
- Oh. I must have missed the... - Mr. Lomanitz?

268
00:17:24,177 --> 00:17:25,445
Nah...

269
